Description: Fix CVE-2016-1000027 (Spring HttpInvokerServiceExporter deserialization RCE).
 The vulnerable class HttpInvokerServiceExporter performs Java deserialization of
 untrusted client-supplied bytes inside readRemoteInvocation(HttpServletRequest,
 InputStream), which can be exploited via gadget chains (e.g. ysoserial) for
 remote code execution. Upstream Spring 6.0.0 removed the entire RPC remoting
 package (commit 5822f1bf, gh-27422); the 5.3.x branch keeps the class as a
 deprecated-but-supported API and the vendor declined to backport a mitigation
 (issue #24434). This derived hardening backport neutralizes the exploitable
 deserialization read path in-place: the method now throws IOException before
 any ObjectInputStream is constructed, so no untrusted bytes are ever
 deserialized. The class, its public constructor, all configuration handling
 and the rest of its API surface remain so dependent code continues to load
 and wire normally; only inbound HTTP invocations that would have triggered
 deserialization are refused. Trusted-data users who relied on the legacy
 protocol must migrate to a non-serialization-based remoting/messaging
 protocol (REST/JSON, gRPC, etc.).
Origin: derived, https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-framework/commit/5822f1bf85b94fd15f9829914b065b1c61910c7d
Bug: https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-framework/issues/27422
Bug: https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-framework/issues/24434
Author: Root.io Patch Platoon <security@root.io>
Last-Update: 2026-06-09

